			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Monk Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Mycroft of the Ashen Order</a> | 
		            1/1/2000 5:00:19 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Greetings and well met my fellow brothers &amp; sisters of the path to perfection. I have waited to post things here until I became skilled in the 20th season of combat,and last night was the big day! So without further ado,let's get to it! ;) This is what I've found to be true:<BR>
<BR>
Don't EVER pick up a weapon! It's the worst thing you can do,we have the skill to use one handed blunt,but don't do it-your hands will outweigh any dammage that a weapon can do...plus,if you die &amp; lose your weapon you will be helpless until you retrive it. You CAN'T lose your fists! Also,don't ever carry ANYTHING in your hands,leave them open so your dual wield will go up faster,trust me - it's worth it. It's one of the only things that gives us an edge over other fighter classes,get it up at soon as you can. Always use only one level point to start a skill,then let it build on it's own,it will go up rather quickly, so save your points for that Feign Death skill at the 17th season - but remember,after awhile the training starts to cost you in a BIG way,so save up some money as well. When I reached the 17th level I dumped about 60 level points into it,along with about 55pp! Worth every copper in my opinion,it's gotten my butt out of more then one tight spot. ;) <BR>
Keep your weight down,I keep mine at about 6 to 7 lbs. at all times,(but we can go up to 14lbs. without any loss of skill)it really seems to help with your dodge,and block skills. I would say unless you have a friend that can make you cured silk armor (the ONLY way to go..)stick with the mesh &amp; woven armor - leather &amp; patchwork is just to heavy to be of any use to us,except in bits &amp; pieces: like some wristbands or boots,good AC without adding TOO much weight,but make the switch when you can. Get WOVEN or MESH gloves first! You want to be able to attack creatures with these magical gloves as soon as you can,and there not that pricey at this stage of the game. Wu's fighters are a great help at higher levels,but not a requirement - and MUCH more spendy then the other types of gloves. Forget about Greater lightstones,they are a JOKE! You are a human and BLIND in the dark,get used ot it! ;) All a GLS did in my opinion was take up what little space I did have in my invintory slots,&amp; with a orc Leggo bracer &amp; a Dervish cutthrout ring get me my orange sash from my Order in Freeport. Learn the Bind Wounds skill right away,this later on combined with your Mend skill will save you ALOT of healing &quot;down time&quot;. Yes,the band-aids cost a bit at low level,but the skill is worth it to bring up,and your mend skill WILL get better - I promise! :) The Instill Doubt is a skill that I'm still working on,so far it seems to do a minor bit of dammage and make your target run away from you. This is not an easy skill to get off(at least not at this level)so I wouldn't worry to much about it at first,but pratice-pratice-pratice! It's bound to come in handy some day. :) Swimming,Safe Fall,and Sneak are not skills I seem to use very much so far,but- like I said,you never know...<BR>
Sence Heading is a MUST for us poor blind humans,when it gets dark outside(&amp; inside for that matter)this skill could mean the differance between getting out of a zone alive,or making that long haul to retrieve your corpse. Pratice it all the time,it WILL get better,and it's our only way to &quot;see&quot; in the dark. <BR>
Last but not least,do your sash quests! (or headband if your from the Silent Fist Order) These items will be a great thing to have at lower levels,and lets other monks you run across know which order you are from,unless your like me and have done both the Sash &amp; Headband quests from both Orders. (Which I would highly suggest that you do) Well,I can't think of anything else to say - &amp; yes,I KNOW it's all been said in one way or another before,but it never hurts to have it worded a little diffrent each time. ;) <BR>
Until I get my Flying kick...I'll leave you with this bit of wisdom:<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A buffed monk,is a DEADLY monk!&quot; <BR>
<BR>
May Quellious bring you enlightment my brothers &amp; sisters. :)<BR>
<BR>
Mycroft of the 20th season<BR>
Brother of the Ashen Order<BR>
Holder of the Red sash<BR>
Prexus <BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
